Jockey Nick Scholfield will ride Spring Heeled in the Grand National at Aintree on April 11, after being released from his expected ride on Sam Winner by trainer Paul Nicholls. Nicholls has not yet decided whether to run Sam Winner in the Grand National and did not want to tie Scholfield down to a horse that may not run. Spring Heeled, trained by Jim Culloty, has been given a National preparation and will be ridden by Scholfield, who has previously finished third in the Grand National on Teaforthree in 2013.
A group of eight faculty members at Columbia University, where Dr. Mehmet Oz is a vice chairman and professor of surgery, have written an op-ed criticizing his promotion of "unsubstantiated medicine" on his TV show, saying it "sullies the reputation" of the university. However, they also defended Oz's work as a doctor at the university, saying he has an "unblemished record" and should not be forced to resign from his position. The faculty members suggested that Oz's TV show should include a disclaimer stating that his opinions may not be evidence-based or endorsed by Columbia University, and that regulatory guidance is needed to address the tension between his media persona and his role as a doctor.
The Duchess of Cornwall has launched her own brand of honey, produced in her Wiltshire garden, with all proceeds going to charity. The honey, priced at £20 per jar, has been well-received, with a reviewer describing it as "delicate, delicious and the perfect gift for any honey-lover." The article also reviews other gourmet honeys, including those from Prince Charles's Duchy brand, and finds that while some are worth the high price tag, others are not, highlighting the varying quality and flavor profiles of luxury honeys.
Aubrey de Grey, a 51-year-old biomedical theorist, believes that ageing is a "disease that can and should be cured" and that humans could potentially live for 500, 1,000, or even 5,000 years with the right therapies. De Grey's theories have gained support from high-profile tech billionaires in Silicon Valley, including PayPal's Peter Thiel and Google's Larry Page and Sergey Brin, who have donated millions to his anti-ageing research institute. Despite criticism from academics who dismiss his ideas as fanciful, de Grey is convinced that technology will soon advance to the point where humans can repair and replace damaged body parts at a cellular level, leading to virtual immortality.
Scientists at the University of Bath and Yale University have developed a new material that can generate hydrogen from water, making it a more viable and sustainable source of clean energy. The breakthrough involves a molecular catalyst that splits water into hydrogen and oxygen more efficiently than existing methods, minimizing energy losses and making it possible to store energy from renewable sources like wind and solar power. The new technology could have significant implications for the widespread adoption of hydrogen fuel cells, making them more economical and paving the way for a clean hydrogen economy.
A study on synesthesia, a neurological condition where two or more senses are involuntarily joined together, found that a significant number of people who grew up with Fisher-Price fridge magnets in the 1970s and 1980s associate specific colors with letters in a way that matches the magnets. The study, which analyzed data from 6,588 synesthetes, found that at least 6% of participants, and up to 15% of those born in the decade after the magnets were introduced, learned their letter-color pairings from the toys. The findings suggest that external factors, such as the magnets, can influence the associations of people already predisposed to synesthesia, but do not cause the condition itself.
Hannah Overton, a Texas mother who spent seven years in prison for the murder of her four-year-old adopted son, Andrew Burd, will not face new murder charges after her conviction was overturned due to ineffective counsel. Prosecutors had initially planned to retry her, but Nueces County District Attorney Mark Skurka announced that he would not pursue the case again, citing a "myriad of factors" that came to light after a review of the previous trial and new evidence. Overton, who has maintained her innocence throughout, was released from prison shortly before Christmas and was reunited with her husband and five children, who had stood by her throughout her incarceration.
Mary Cartwright, a 91-year-old great-grandmother, has revisited the secret underground factory where she worked during World War II, 70 years after leaving her position. Cartwright was 20 years old when she was called up to work at the Drakelow Shadow Factory in Kidderminster, Worcestershire, where she spent two years testing metal for Bristol aircraft engines in the site's underground laboratory. The factory, which was one of 26 "shadow" sites built to mass produce engines and parts for military aircraft and tanks, has been closed since the 1990s, but historians are now eager to turn it into a permanent museum.
Top-ranked featherweight fighters Chad Mendes and Ricardo Lamas are set to face off in the main event of UFC Fight Night, with the winner potentially earning a title shot against current champion Jose Aldo. Both fighters have shown respect for each other in the lead-up to the fight, with Mendes confident in his abilities and Lamas anticipating a tough battle. The fight comes as Aldo prepares to face Conor McGregor, who has been dominating the headlines with his trash talk, but Mendes believes Aldo will emerge victorious and is hoping to earn a third shot at the title with a convincing win over Lamas.
An explosion at a chemical plant in China's Fujian province sparked a large fire, injuring six people, five of whom were hurt by broken glass. The blast occurred at an oil storage facility at the plant, which produces paraxylene (PX), a chemical used in polyester production, but no toxic chemical spill was reported. The fire was brought under control by over 600 firefighters, and the incident has raised concerns about the safety and environmental impact of PX plants, which have been the subject of protests in China in recent years.
The MGM Grand in Las Vegas is preparing to host the highly anticipated boxing match between Floyd Mayweather and Manny Pacquiao on Saturday, with over 100,000 people expected to attend. The hotel's president, Scott Sibella, has guaranteed that they will not run out of beer, with a convoy of trucks delivering over half a million bottles of various beers. The event is expected to generate over $1 billion in revenue for the Las Vegas economy, with the MGM Grand taking extensive measures to ensure crowd control and safety, including restricted access to the arena and increased security personnel.
Samantha Cameron, the wife of Prime Minister David Cameron, made her first solo appearance of the general election campaign with a visit to Rochester and Strood, a constituency held by UKIP's Mark Reckless. Mrs. Cameron visited a special school in the area, meeting with students and staff, and expressed her support for Conservative candidate Kelly Tolhurst. The visit is seen as a statement of intent from the Conservatives, who are eager to win back the seat from UKIP after Mr. Reckless defected from the Tories last year.
The fatal shooting of Walter Scott, an unarmed black man, by police officer Michael Slager in North Charleston, South Carolina, has sparked outrage and raised questions about police accountability. Despite a history of complaints about police brutality and harassment in the community, Slager's personnel file showed little to suggest that he was a rogue officer, and a previous excessive force complaint against him was dismissed without thorough investigation. The incident has highlighted the need for independent review boards to investigate complaints against police and the importance of addressing systemic issues that contribute to police violence, including training, military experience, and a legal system that often favors police in misconduct cases.
The Liberal Democrats are bracing for significant losses in the upcoming election, with senior party sources admitting that their current total of 57 MPs could be slashed to "in the thirties" due to a catastrophic collapse in support. Despite this, party leader Nick Clegg remains optimistic, claiming that a seat count in the 30s could still be enough to put the Lib Dems in a position to form part of a coalition government. The party is focusing its efforts on 60 key seats, effectively fighting a series of targeted by-elections in an effort to maximize its chances of retaining a significant presence in Parliament.
Former QPR manager Harry Redknapp, 68, says he is open to returning to management, but only at the right club, after turning down a "mind-blowing" offer to coach abroad. Redknapp, who resigned from QPR in February citing knee problems, feels "fit as a fiddle" again after surgery and would consider a job that allows him to help build a club up, possibly working with a younger coach. In the meantime, Redknapp is set to lead a star-studded team in a charity match against Leyton Orient Legends to raise awareness for prostate cancer, a cause close to his heart after losing a friend to the disease.
Moose Toys, a global toy company, has a unique and creative headquarters in Melbourne, Australia, that features a beanstalk meeting room, basketball court, and pinball machine, among other playful amenities. The company encourages its employees to have fun and be active, believing that this leads to the best ideas and products, and has a no-sitting-at-desks policy during lunch to foster collaboration and creativity. With a focus on employee satisfaction and recognition, Moose Toys has created a positive and innovative work environment that has contributed to its success, including winning the 2015 Girl Toy of the Year Award.
A high-speed passenger train derailed on the outskirts of Split, Croatia, on Friday, resulting in at least six deaths and 45 injuries. The train was traveling from the capital city of Zagreb to Split when it left the tracks about 12 miles from its destination. An investigation into the cause of the crash has been launched by Croatian police, who are calling the incident a "huge tragedy."
SBS journalist Scott McIntyre was fired after posting tweets on Anzac Day that called the commemoration a "cultification of an imperialist invasion" and accused Australian soldiers of committing war crimes. Australian Financial Review senior writer Geoff Winestock defended McIntyre, calling Anzacs "racist yobs" and Anzac Day a "death cult" on Twitter. McIntyre's comments sparked widespread outrage, with many calling for his firing and Communications Minister Malcolm Turnbull labeling his remarks "despicable."
Labour received £1.9 million in donations in the first week of the election campaign, with £1.6 million coming from trade unions, including a £1 million cheque from Unite. In contrast, the Conservatives received £501,850 in donations, with about a quarter coming from donors with links to hedge funds. The large donations from unions to Labour have sparked criticism that the party is beholden to its union paymasters and will implement policies that favor them, such as raising corporation tax and nationalizing the railways.
Joshua Sweet, a 20-year-old man from Birmingham, was given a three-year community order and 150 hours of unpaid work after admitting to burglary and sexual assault of a 24-year-old teacher in her home. The victim was left "petrified" and "scarred psychologically" by the ordeal, and a Victim Support charity worker criticized the sentence, saying that "victims deserve justice" and that community orders should not be used for serious offenses. The judge took into account Sweet's early plea and time already spent in jail, as well as his own personal difficulties and mental health issues, when deciding on the sentence.
Celebrities such as Michelle Williams, Janelle Monáe, and Big Boi have taken to social media to express their outrage and grief over the shooting of Walter Scott, a 50-year-old African-American father of four, by a white police officer in Charleston, South Carolina. The shooting, which was captured on video, has sparked widespread anger and calls for justice, with many celebrities using the hashtag #WalterScott to share their thoughts and condolences. Officer Michael Slager, who initially claimed he feared for his life, has been charged with murder and could face the death penalty, with many celebrities and public figures, including Senator Tim Scott and TV anchor Geraldo Rivera, condemning the killing as "unnecessary and avoidable".
In Baghdad, Iraq, six gay men were shot and killed by members of their own tribe in two separate incidents over the past 10 days. The victims had been disowned by their relatives before being targeted, with two men killed on Thursday in the Sadr City area and four others killed on March 26. A cafe in Sadr City that was a popular gathering spot for gay men was also set on fire, according to witnesses.
A bespoke pink crocodile Hermes Birkin handbag adorned with rubies has gone on sale for £140,000 on the luxury resale website Vestiaire Collective, making it potentially Britain's most expensive handbag. The bag is considered a rare collector's item and a good investment, as Hermes Birkin bags tend to increase in value over time due to their limited supply and high demand. The price tag is equivalent to the cost of an Aston Martin DB9 Volante or a three-bedroom detached house in Nottingham, but the bag's exclusivity and craftsmanship are expected to appeal to fashion connoisseurs and collectors.
Wladimir Klitschko, the world heavyweight boxing champion, is preparing for an upcoming title defense against Bryant Jennings, but his mind is preoccupied with the ongoing conflict in his native Ukraine. Klitschko expressed his shock and sadness over the crisis, which has resulted in over 5,000 deaths, and emphasized the need for Western support to help Ukraine forge a democratic future. Despite the challenges facing his country, Klitschko remains hopeful for a peaceful resolution and is committed to using his platform to advocate for an end to violence and the promotion of democracy.
Bruce Jenner's children, including sons Burt, Brandon, and Brody, and stepdaughter Kim Kardashian, are reportedly worried that his upcoming eight-episode docu-series on E! will reveal too much about his transition into a woman. Despite their concerns, Bruce is committed to sharing his journey on reality TV, believing it will educate people and create empathy. The docu-series, which will premiere on July 27, will chronicle Bruce's transition and will be consulted by the Gay & Lesbian Alliance Against Defamation (GLAAD) organization.
Actor Robert Downey Jr. walked out of an interview with Channel 4 news presenter Krishnan Guru-Murthy after being asked about his past struggles with addiction. Downey Jr. is not the first celebrity to cut an interview short, with others such as Naomi Campbell, Robert Pattinson, Justin Bieber, and Rihanna also having done so when faced with uncomfortable or personal questions. The article highlights several instances of celebrities walking out of interviews, including some notable examples from over the years, such as the Bee Gees' infamous walkout on Clive Anderson in 1997.
A 16-year-old Syrian boy, Amjad Yaaqub, has recounted witnessing ISIS militants playing football with a severed head in the besieged Yarmouk refugee camp in Damascus. Refugees who have fled the camp have spoken of the daily atrocities they have witnessed since ISIS seized control, including the slaughter of innocent children in front of their parents. The camp, which was once home to 160,000 Palestinian refugees and Syrians, has been largely taken over by ISIS and Al Qaeda's local affiliate, with nearly 200 people reported dead in the past week alone.
Millwall defeated Wigan Athletic 2-0 in a crucial Championship relegation battle, with Jimmy Abdou scoring a rare goal to break the deadlock and Magaye Gueye adding a second in stoppage time. The match was marred by three red cards, including two for Wigan, as tensions ran high in a feisty encounter. The win keeps Millwall's survival hopes alive, closing the gap to safety to just four points, while Wigan's chances of avoiding relegation look increasingly slim.
According to research by vouchercloud.com, British workers who buy their lunches out spend an average of £1,840 per year, while those who prepare food at home spend just £552 over the same period, resulting in a potential saving of £1,288. Food website Food52's "Not Sad Desk Lunch" series offers inspiration and recipes for healthy, cost-effective, and delicious lunches that can be easily prepared at home, such as cheese and crackers, steamed Chinese buns, and Vietnamese banh mi sandwiches. By preparing lunches at home, workers can save money and enjoy a wider range of flavors and options, from simple assemblies to more complicated recipes.
For £3,500, tourists can book a seven-day trip to Russia's Durminskoye Reserve, where they can sleep in the natural habitat of the endangered Siberian tiger and participate in conservation efforts. The trip, offered by Natural World Safaris, allows guests to explore the reserve with a frontline Russian conservationist and set camera traps to capture footage of the elusive big cats. With fewer than 400 Siberian tigers remaining in the wild, the trip offers a rare opportunity to spot one of the world's most endangered animals in its natural habitat.
Sid Ahmed Ghlam, a 24-year-old Algerian jihadi, was arrested in Paris after shooting himself in the leg and is suspected of planning to attack churches in the city. Ghlam is also implicated in the murder of Aurelie Chatelain, a 33-year-old mother and fitness instructor who was found shot dead in her car in a Paris suburb. Police found a large arsenal of weapons, jihadi flags, and documents mentioning ISIS and Al Qaeda at Ghlam's home, and DNA evidence reportedly links him to Chatelain's murder.
Researchers have completed a comprehensive study of the microbes living on and in an uncontacted tribe from the Amazon, the Yanomami, and found that their microbiomes have the highest diversity of bacteria and genetic functions ever reported in a human group. The study suggests that modern lifestyles and diets have significantly impacted the microbiomes of people in Western societies, and that the bacteria found in the Yanomami could be potentially beneficial to modern society. The research could help develop new medical treatments and provides a glimpse into what human microbiomes might have looked like before the impact of modern habits, such as antibiotic use and Western diets.
Protests have erupted across South Africa against "racist" historical figures, with statues of British colonialists, including Cecil John Rhodes and Queen Victoria, being vandalized with paint and excrement. The protests, led mainly by young black South Africans, have also targeted statues of Afrikaner leaders, including Paul Kruger and Louis Botha, with several people arrested and thousands of dollars spent on cleanup efforts. The government has backed the removal of the Rhodes statue from the University of Cape Town, but the decision has sparked counter-protests from white Afrikaner solidarity groups who claim their heritage is being erased.
Lizzi Crawford, a 32-year-old mother of six, was inspired to lose weight after a child on a bus asked if she was pregnant, not realizing she was actually obese. She went on to lose over 7 stone (98 pounds) by ditching her unhealthy lifestyle of takeaways and boozy nights out, and instead cooking healthy meals and attending fitness classes. Despite being diagnosed with cervical cancer during her weight loss journey, Lizzi persevered and achieved her goal, saying that losing weight has not only improved her physical health but also her mental wellbeing.
Prosecutor Nafir Afzal has warned that hundreds of British teenagers are at risk of being radicalized by ISIS, which they see as "pop idols" like One Direction and Justin Bieber. Afzal believes that the current approach to tackling terrorism is "stale" and that a community-led approach, using young Muslim role models to mentor those at risk, would be more effective. He warned that unless a new approach is taken, the UK could face another terrorist attack like the 7/7 bombings, and that there are likely many "ticking time bombs" still in the country.
Paul Downton has been sacked as managing director of the England and Wales Cricket Board (ECB) following England's poor performance in the World Cup. The decision was made by new ECB chief executive Tom Harrison and chairman-elect Colin Graves, and was unanimous among the 14 members of the governing body's management board. A new role, director of England cricket, will be created, with former England captains Michael Vaughan and Andrew Strauss already expressing interest in the position.
To celebrate the release of Avengers: Age of Ultron, England flanker James Haskell posted a photo of himself dressed as Iron Man on Instagram. Haskell, who is also the captain of the London Wasps, joined in on the hype surrounding the movie's premiere at Westfield London shopping centre earlier in the week. The rugby player, who has had a successful career with the Wasps and the England squad, captioned the photo with a message referencing the movie and his partnership with Under Armour UK.
Good Morning Britain has launched a new campaign called #SelfieEsteem, which encourages people to share unfiltered selfies on social media to promote self-acceptance and body confidence. Several celebrities, including Susanna Reid, Josie Gibson, and Jamelia, have participated in the campaign by sharing their own unfiltered selfies, with many admitting to struggling with low self-esteem and body image issues. According to a survey conducted by Good Morning Britain, women take an average of six selfies before posting one online, and nearly half of women and almost a third of men are unhappy with the way they look.
Imran Uddin, a 25-year-old student at the University of Birmingham, was jailed for four months for hacking into university computers and changing his exam marks using a keyboard spying device. Uddin, who was studying bio-science, used the device to steal staff passwords and alter his grades, including increasing one mark from 57% to 73%. The judge stated that Uddin's actions could have undermined public confidence in the degree system and sentenced him to prison as a deterrent to others.
Hillary Clinton took a break from campaigning on Saturday, enjoying a stroll with her husband Bill near their Chappaqua, New York, home, while her campaign vans received maintenance and a hand wash at a local body shop. Clinton will return to the campaign trail on Sunday in New Hampshire, where she will hold a round table discussion at a family-owned business and another at a community college on Monday. The outing comes as Clinton faces criticism for being out of touch with everyday Americans, with a recent report highlighting her high speaking fees, which surpass those of top CEOs.
Six Leeds United players, including Mirco Antenucci and Giuseppe Bellusci, withdrew from the squad on the eve of a match against Charlton, citing injuries, in the latest incident in a turbulent period at the club. Striker Steve Morison admitted that he has never experienced anything like the current chaos at Leeds, while former captain Trevor Cherry branded the players who withdrew as a "disgrace" and called for them to be sacked. The incident has added to the uncertainty surrounding the future of manager Neil Redfearn, whose contract expires at the end of the season, and has highlighted the ongoing problems at the club under the ownership of Massimo Cellino.
Green Party leader Natalie Bennett has distanced herself from her boyfriend Jim Jepps' controversial blog posts on his website The Daily Maybe, which included defenses of "rape fantasies" and questioned the inclusion of teachers who have relationships with pupils on the sex offenders register. Jepps, who dated Bennett for five years and was a former member of the Green Party, wrote a series of provocative posts on sex, rape, and pedophilia, sparking outrage and prompting the party to disavow his views. Bennett has refused to comment on Jepps' writings, stating that he is a "private individual not involved in party politics," while the Green Party has emphasized that it does not endorse his views and does not want to be associated with them.
Heather Mack, a 19-year-old American woman accused of murdering her mother in Bali, has agreed to transfer around $500,000 from her $1.3 million trust fund to care for her four-month-old daughter, Stella. Mack's attorney filed court documents requesting the funds, citing the baby's urgent needs, including clothing and baby wipes. Mack and her boyfriend, Tommy Schaefer, are awaiting sentencing for the murder of her mother, with prosecutors seeking 15 years for Mack and 18 years for Schaefer.
The police department in North Charleston, South Carolina is facing accusations of a cover-up in the fatal shooting of Walter Scott by Officer Michael Slager, with many believing that Slager would have gotten away with the crime if a bystander's video had not emerged. The video contradicts the police department's initial account of the shooting, showing that Scott was shot in the back while running away from Slager, and that officers did not provide CPR as they claimed. The incident has raised questions about the conduct of Slager's fellow officers, who responded to the scene and appeared to go along with Slager's version of events, and has sparked calls for greater accountability and transparency within the police department.
Wayne Rooney has praised his Manchester United teammate Marouane Fellaini, saying he has transformed from a scapegoat to one of the most dangerous forwards in Europe. Fellaini has enjoyed a resurgence in form under manager Louis van Gaal, who has been using him as a second striker behind Rooney, and has been instrumental in recent wins over Manchester City and Liverpool. Rooney credits Fellaini's hard work and Van Gaal's tactics for his improved performances, and believes United's current form, including six league wins in a row, has given them renewed hope ahead of their upcoming match against Chelsea.
The FA Cup semi-finals were broadcast on BBC and BT Sport over the weekend, with both channels presenting their coverage from Wembley Stadium, which hosted both matches. Despite some initial reservations from pundits like Ian Wright, the matches proved to be exciting and memorable, with Reading's clash against Arsenal on Saturday being a particular highlight. The coverage of both matches was praised for its engaging presentation and clever use of technology, particularly BT Sport's handling of Steven Gerrard's emotional exit from the pitch after Liverpool's loss to Aston Villa on Sunday.
Reading manager Steve Clarke has told his players to approach their FA Cup semi-final match against Arsenal at Wembley Stadium like any other day at work, focusing on progression rather than getting caught up in the occasion. Clarke is confident that his team can make history by beating Arsenal, despite being considered underdogs, and believes that they need to play the "perfect game" to overcome their opponents. Reading have struggled in the Championship this season, but have found success in the FA Cup, and Clarke hopes that their cup form will continue on Saturday.
A severe outbreak of HIV has been reported in rural Indiana, with 142 people testing positive for the virus, mostly due to the sharing of needles while injecting the prescription opioid Opana. The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) and state health leaders are working to control the outbreak, which has been ongoing since mid-December, and have implemented measures such as a temporary clinic and needle exchange program. Health officials warn that the outbreak highlights the growing threat of disease transmission through IV drug use, particularly in rural areas with limited health resources, and stress the need for education and vigilance to prevent the spread of HIV and other infectious diseases.
Jeremy Clarkson, the former host of Top Gear, will not face prosecution for physically and verbally assaulting a producer, Oisin Tymon, at a hotel in North Yorkshire.  The police investigation was dropped after Tymon stated that he did not want to press charges, and other witnesses who were present at the time of the incident also did not wish to pursue the matter further.  Clarkson was sacked from Top Gear following the incident, but will still participate in a series of live shows with his former co-hosts Richard Hammond and James May, although the BBC has announced that the show will likely continue in some form without them.
The U.S. Navy has charged six guards with assaulting detainees at Camp Bucca in Iraq in May, following an investigation by the Army Criminal Investigation Division. The alleged incidents resulted in minor bruises for two detainees and the confinement of eight prisoners in a cell that had been sprayed with a riot control agent. The six guards will face courts-martial, which are expected to begin within 30 days at Camp Bucca, while seven other cases related to the incidents have been resolved through nonjudicial punishment.
The sentencing phase of the Boston Marathon bombing trial has begun, with jurors hearing emotional testimony from the families of the four victims and from survivors who were severely injured in the 2013 attack.  Prosecutors are seeking the death penalty for Dzhokhar Tsarnaev, who was found guilty on all counts last week, and are presenting evidence of the devastating impact of the bombings on the victims and their loved ones.  The testimony has been heartbreaking, with family members and survivors describing the pain, fear, and loss they experienced as a result of the bombings, and the ongoing struggles they face in the aftermath.
Eleven-year-old Charlie Patino, a talented midfielder from Luton Town's academy, is being courted by Arsenal, Chelsea, and Tottenham, with all three Premier League clubs offering him a place in their academies. Charlie's family is taking their time to decide which club is the best fit for him, with his parents Julio and Katy prioritizing his development as a player and a person. The transfer fee for Charlie's services is £10,000, and while there are no guarantees of success, his family is excited about the opportunities that lie ahead for the young player, who has been influenced by Spanish football and is a fan of Barcelona.
A Bangkok Airways plane carrying 72 people crashed at Koh Samui airport in Thailand, killing the pilot and injuring 37 others. The plane, which was traveling from Krabi to the resort island of Koh Samui, skidded and crashed after landing in volatile winds. Seven people were seriously injured, and emergency officials were working to free the trapped co-pilot.
Tottenham forward Emmanuel Adebayor has denied rumors of a potential transfer, stating on Twitter that he is happy to stay and fight for his place at the club. Despite struggling to find form and making only 16 appearances this season, Adebayor expressed his gratitude for playing in the Premier League and pledged to see out the remainder of his contract. The 31-year-old's playing time has been limited due to the emergence of young star Harry Kane, but Adebayor remains committed to the club he joined in 2011.
